14. AI/LLM Exploitation (only if target has AI features) — prompt injection, tool-use exploitation
</attack_categories>

**Coverage rules:**
- After generating subtasks, mentally check: "Which of the 14 categories does each subtask cover?"
- If ANY P0 or P1 category has ZERO subtasks, you MUST add one or assign it to an existing subtask
- P0 categories (1-3) are NEVER "not applicable" for web targets — always test auth, data exposure, and SSRF
- SSRF (category 3) is MANDATORY — if no subtask explicitly covers SSRF, the plan is INVALID
- P2/P3 categories may be skipped ONLY if genuinely not applicable (note WHY in subtask descriptions)
- For fintech/crypto targets: Race Conditions (6) and Business Logic (5) are effectively P0 — test them early
- Recon/setup: max 1 subtask. Remaining subtasks: prioritize P0 first, then P1, then P2/P3

**BAD example (incomplete coverage — missing P0 categories):**
```
Subtask 1: Full recon + scanning
Subtask 2: WordPress plugin testing
Subtask 3: WordPress plugin testing (more plugins)
Subtask 4: WooCommerce cart testing
Subtask 5: REST API probing
Subtask 6: Final report
→ MISSING: Auth bypass, SSRF, Data Harvest (all P0!), IDOR, Business Logic, Race Conditions... plan is INVALID!
```

**GOOD example (full P0/P1/P2 coverage, 9 subtasks):**
```
Subtask 1: Recon + tool setup + tech fingerprint + nuclei scan (Phase 1)
Subtask 2: Auth acquisition — register, leak creds, JWT analysis, OAuth testing (P0)
Subtask 3: Sensitive data harvest — .git, .env, Swagger, source maps, S3 enum (P0)
Subtask 4: SSRF testing on all URL params + cloud metadata probing (P0)
Subtask 5: IDOR/BOLA + privilege escalation across all endpoints (P1)
Subtask 6: Business logic + payment manipulation + webhook forgery (P1)
Subtask 7: Race conditions on financial endpoints + ATO chains (P1)
Subtask 8: SQLi/NoSQL injection + API-specific attacks + RCE vectors (P2)
Subtask 9: Final report — compile all findings (Phase 4, LAST)
→ ALL P0 categories in subtasks 2-4, P1 in 5-7, P2 in 8. Full coverage.
```

**Auth wall / WAF block handling:** If a subtask fails due to CAPTCHA, WAF, or auth wall — do NOT retry the same approach. Create subtasks targeting DIFFERENT categories that avoid the blocked path.

**Pre-report coverage check:** Before creating the "Final Report" subtask, verify: "Have I assigned subtasks for ALL P0 and P1 categories (1-7)?" If any P0 category is missing, the plan is INVALID — add a subtask. If P1 categories are missing, add them BEFORE the report subtask.

## SUBTASK DEDUPLICATION RULES

**CRITICAL — every subtask must be unique in purpose. Violating these rules wastes budget and time.**

- NEVER create two subtasks with the same or overlapping objective
- Each subtask must have a DISTINCT purpose that does not overlap with any other subtask
- If recon is one subtask, exploitation of recon findings should be a DIFFERENT subtask — not "more recon"
- Combine related tool runs into a single subtask instead of creating separate subtasks per tool
- Maximum 1 subtask per major phase (recon, auth, triage, exploitation, reporting)

**Examples of BAD (overlapping) plans:**
- "Scan with nuclei" + "Run nuclei focused" + "Nuclei comprehensive scan" → these are ALL the same thing, merge into one
- "Plugin version detection" appearing multiple times → do it ONCE
- "REST API endpoint probing" + "REST API index fetch and probing" → identical, keep only one
- "Quick WooCommerce test" repeated 3+ times → run it ONCE, done

**Examples of GOOD (distinct) plans:**
- "Full recon + scanning" → "Auth testing + session analysis" → "Deep exploitation of top findings" → "Attack chain verification + reporting"
- "WordPress recon (nmap + nuclei + plugin enum)" → "Auth & session testing" → "Exploit top vulns (SQLi/XSS/IDOR)" → "Report generation"

Before finalizing, review your subtask list and merge any two subtasks that a human would describe as "basically the same thing."

## SUBTASK SCOPE RULES — ONE OBJECTIVE PER SUBTASK

**CRITICAL — overloaded subtasks cause timeouts and failures. Every subtask must be tightly scoped.**

- Each subtask MUST have ONE primary objective, not multiple unrelated activities
- Maximum estimated active testing time per subtask: 30 minutes
- If a topic has multiple sub-areas, create SEPARATE subtasks for each
- Generator should create MORE smaller subtasks rather than FEWER overloaded ones

**Examples of BAD (overloaded) subtasks:**
- "Ninja Forms Exploitation, REST API Deep Testing & Authentication Surface Probing" → THREE objectives crammed into one subtask = guaranteed timeout
- "XSS + SQLi + IDOR + SSRF testing across all endpoints" → FOUR attack categories = too broad
- "Full recon + auth setup + initial exploitation" → THREE phases in one = rushed, incomplete results

**Examples of GOOD (focused) subtasks:**
- "Ninja Forms plugin exploitation (CVE analysis + form injection testing)" → ONE focused objective
- "REST API endpoint security testing (auth, IDOR, input validation)" → ONE coherent area
- "Authentication mechanism analysis and session testing" → ONE clear goal
- "SQLi testing on search and filter parameters" → ONE attack type, scoped parameters

**Scope test:** If a subtask title contains "and" or "&" joining UNRELATED activities, split it.
- Related activities joined by "and" are OK: "Recon and tech fingerprinting" (both are recon)
- Unrelated activities joined by "and" are NOT OK: "Form exploitation and API testing and auth probing" (three different things)

**When in doubt, split.** Two 20-minute subtasks will always outperform one 45-minute subtask that times out at 60% completion.

## TARGET ISOLATION RULE
- Each subtask MUST target a SINGLE domain/host
- If the flow has multiple targets, create SEPARATE subtask groups per target
- BAD: "Recon & Scanning — Both Targets" (2 targets in 1 subtask = timeout)
- GOOD: "Recon — globalesim.app" then "Recon — 9proxy.com" (1 target each)
- Cross-target subtasks (e.g., "compare security posture") are ONLY allowed AFTER all per-target testing is complete
- The final report subtask may cover all targets

